The '''chestnut rail''' ('''''Gallirallus castaneoventris''''') is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Rallidae]].
It is found in the [[Aru Islands]] and northern [[Australia]].
Its natural [[habitat]] is [[subtropical]] or [[tropical]] [[mangrove|mangrove forests]]. It was formerly the only species placed in the genus ''Eulabeornis''.

Their [[Bird nest|nests]] are shaped into platforms and range in size from 35–50&nbsp;cm in diameter, and 5–10&nbsp;cm in depth. They are built in mangrove trees out of predominantly mangrove sticks, along with some leaves and [[seedling]]s.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Barnes |first=Terry A. |last2=Franklin |first2=Donald C |date=1997 |title=Notes on the Nests of the Chestnut Rail |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/55648335#page/7/mode/1up |journal=Northern Territory Naturalist |volume=15 |pages=6–11 |via=Biodiversity Heritage Library}}</ref> [[Clutch (eggs)|Clutch]] size ranges from 2-4 eggs per brood.  
